@georgeke here's another good ramp task if you want to pick this up

@georgeke & @mistercrunch I don't know if it's an easy part to add, but
role inheritance would be really useful at some point too - and not just in
the config file but also in their live incarnations too.

As background, I have a base "viewer" user (very similar to the Gamma
user), and there are some datasources that I'd like to only give access to
for particular users (for arguments sake call them "finance"), but they
should otherwise have exactly the same rights as the "viewer" users. If the
"finance" use could inherit from "viewer" and only add the additional data
sources that would mean not maintaining two parallel roles with almost
identical privileges.

Thanks!

I just got it to working. Here is what I did - 

```
brew install pkg-config libffi openssl python
env LDFLAGS="-L$(brew --prefix openssl)/lib" CFLAGS="-I$(brew --prefix openssl)/include" pip install cryptography
```

The `pip install cryptography` did not work. But, I did a `conda install cryptography` instead and got it set up.

After that, it was just `pip install caravel`

So it doesn't seem to matter whether the grouped column (trans_day) is marked as dttm column. It has the same error no matter what. So It must be auto detected the YYYY-MM-DD format and trying to do something with it?

@asydorchuk 
Yes, that's one of the differences. I know it can be done by configuring the permissions, but
1. the permission setting is so complicated and is already a mess (to me). There are already too many permissions and it's confusing and not straightforward for the users. The users don't know what permissions can be tweaked and permissions for different purposes are all mixed together in one place. You can see the problem by looking at the long list of permissions of Admin and Alpha roles. By moving it to a separate place, it will be clear and specific. and 
2. we don't have to create permissions for each dashboard. if we have 30 dashboards, we will have to create 30 permissions. It's, again, too complicated to me.

I really wished I could reuse the logic of the permissions. If you still don't think it's a good idea to create another table for dashboard access, maybe another thing we should do is to improve the permission editing page to make it straightforward to the users.
Or maybe keep the new form field "role access" in this pull request, but when the form is saved, finish the logic using ab_permission instead of a new table. But I am not sure if it is feasible.
Any reason why this stalled?
@x4base, sounds reasonable to me, however I am not the owner of the repo. You probably need to update existing datasource_access permission checks.

I am working on an Apache Drill Sql Alchemy Dialect. I have some basic things working, and have been working with others on the Drill mailing list.  There has been talk of plugging Drill to Elastic Search, which seems a bit convoluted, however, since Elasticsearch doesn't have a SQL interface, Drill works really nice, if we get a Dialect working for Drill, then other storage plugins will (hopefully) just work. Some of the work can be found here:

Docker container with pyodbc, unixodbc, Drill ODBC, and caravel all working:

https://github.com/JohnOmernik/caraveldrill

Drill Dialect (work in progress, feel free to play with it and try it, please report issues as you find them, this is iterative brute force programming at this point!)
https://github.com/JohnOmernik/sqlalchemy-drill
